sentences: Tony Mott (born Anthony Moulds, April 1956) is an English-born Australian rock and music photographer.
Mott was born Anthony Moulds in April 1956, child of Brian and Mary Moulds, and raised in Sheffield, England.
He was a student at Jordanthorpre Comprehensive secondary school, and trained as a chef at Sheffield Polytechnic before arriving in Australia in 1976.
He worked for six months as a chef in Sydney at the Opera House and at the Gazebo Hotel in Kings Cross in 1976, before helping establish a restaurant in Armidale, New South Wales.
Returning to Sydney, he decided to settle in Australia permanently in 1981.
Mott's career as a rock  photographer began in 1983 at the Piccadilly Hotel in Kings Cross.

Mott's portraits have become the best known images of many musicians and bands; examples include Chrissy Amplett of the Divinyls at the Piccadilly Hotel, Kings Cross, 1983; the classic shot of Peter Garrett at the Sydney Entertainment Centre in 1985; the much published portrait of Icelandic singer Björk at the Big Day Out, 1994; the defining shot of Sex Pistols singer Johnny Rotten (Lydon) at the Hordern Pavilion, Sydney, 1994; and the dynamic portraits of Kylie Minogue and Nick Cave who sang the duet "Where the Wild Roses Grow", 1996.

sentences: Music festivals were another fertile source of photographs for Mott from the late 1980s.
In a career spanning more than 30 years, his photographs have appeared in local and international magazines, newspapers, and album covers.
Mott trained as a French and pastry chef and spent 10 years working in hotels in the United Kingdom and in Australia.
He worked for six months as a chef in Sydney at the Opera House and at the Gazebo Hotel in Kings Cross in 1976, before helping establish a restaurant in Armidale, New South Wales.
Mott then worked as a chef aboard the cruise ship SS Oriana for two years, visiting more than 60 countries and developing an interest in travel and photography.
Whilst resuming work as a chef at the Gazebo Hotel in Kings Cross, Mott pursued his love of music, exploring Sydney's live music scene in the evenings.
Mott went to see the Sydney band the Divinyls on Monday nights at the hotel and began photographing the band's lead singer Chrissy Amphlett.
